    data = train_data.copy()

    plt.show()

#Lets understand the distribution of continuous variable features in using histograms

for feature in continuous_columns:

    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.title(feature)
    plt.show()

From the above visualizations it is evident that except 'SalePrice' other features are not normally distributed. Since in regression problems, the data distribution being normally distributed improves the performance and helps gradient descent converge faster, lets make the possible features 'log normally' distributed

In [63]:
#Conversion from random to log normal distribution on possible features

for feature in continuous_columns:
    if feature != 'SalePrice':
        data=train_data.copy()
        data['SalePrice']=np.log(data['SalePrice'])
        if 0 in data[feature].unique():   #Since log(0) is infinite we cant apply log normalalization to the features with '0' in it!
            pass
        else:
            data[feature]=np.log(data[feature])
            data['SalePrice']=np.log(data['SalePrice'])
            data[feature].hist(bins=25)
            plt.xlabel(feature)
            plt.ylabel("Count")
            plt.title(feature)
            plt.show()

#Handling discrete numeric null values(Actually there's no null value in this set)

discreteNa = [feature for feature in featuresNa if feature in discrete_columns]

for feature in discreteNa:
    # Adding a new binary feature, 0 - was not null 1 - was null  
    train_data[feature+'Na'] = np.where(train_data[feature].isnull(),1,0)
    # Filling null values with mode as the features are discrete numeric
    train_data[feature] = train_data[feature].fillna(train_data[feature].mode())

train_data[discreteNa].isnull().sum()

Series([], dtype: float64)
In [154]:
#Handling continuous numeric null values

# Used 'numerical_columns' because 'GarageYrBlt' has been seperated in continuous_columns
continuousNa = [feature for feature in featuresNa if feature in numerical_columns]

for feature in continuousNa:
    # Adding a new binary feature, 0 - was not null 1 - was null  
    train_data[feature+'Na'] = np.where(train_data[feature].isnull(),1,0)
    # Filling null values with median as there are many outliers in the continuous numerical features
    train_data[feature] = train_data[feature].fillna(train_data[feature].median())

train_data[continuousNa].isnull().sum()

#Encoding the categorical features with higher values for those categories in which SalesPrice is high

for feature in categorical_columns:
    order = train_data.groupby([feature])['SalePrice'].mean().sort_values().index
    ordered_dict={k:i for i,k in enumerate(order,0)}
    train_data[feature]=train_data[feature].map(ordered_dict)

#Feature scaling

#Dropping id and seperating our dependant variable 'SalePrice' before doing feature scaling

train_data = train_data.drop(['Id','SalePrice'],axis = 1)

features_to_scale = [feature for feature in train_data.columns if feature not in ['Id','SalePrice']]

normalizer = MinMaxScaler()
train_data = pd.DataFrame(normalizer.fit_transform(train_data[features_to_scale]),columns = [features_to_scale])
